body:
ever since new york//h.s.

The last time you saw Harry was in his Manhattan apartment. You woke up at 3 a.m. and felt like you needed to LEAVE. You knew it would hurt him. You didnt even leave a note. You just boarded the next train to Maine and stayed there for years. And now, you’re back in New York. You’re nervous, thinking you’ll see him, even though the chances were low. You switched your number when you moved so he couldn’t contact you. You knew it was wrong to ghost him. But you just felt so suffocated. As much you loved him, you just couldn’t be there anymore. Though looking back, you know you could’ve been more mature. It’s when you’re thinking about this that you run into someone. Him. But you don’t know that yet.

“Sorry!” You say to the person you bumped into, and lean down to grab the little box that had fallen from his hands. He doesn’t respond until you place the box in his hands. You pull back fast, as if slapped, when you realize who it is.

“Are you?” He says, his hazel eyes burning into yours.

“Oh my God.” You say. You want to run, but suddenly you’ve lost all feeling in your legs. Your hands are shaking at your sides. He’s just watching you, almost sadistically, but also sadly, as if a flood of memories crashed onto him. Which they probably did.

“Y/n.” He said, softly, as if for the first time. You wanted to cry, despite– no, not despite. Because. Because it was your fault.

He’s a little taller, his hair a little longer, but just as beautiful as he was the first day you ever met him.

“You’re back.” He says, then laughs coldly. “Not for me, I suppose.”

“Business.” You manage to croak.

You stand there and stare at each other, studying your faces. Finally, he scrubs a hand through his curls– a tick you were so used to, you almost don’t realize it, even after all these years.

“I’m going to give you my number now.” He says. “I dont know how long you’re going to be here. And I’m not going to wait for your call, not this time. But you have my number. Call if you… want to.”

You watched numbly as he grabbed your hand, his soft touch making your chest jump. He wrote his number on the side of your hand in pen, but you dont focus, don’t question why he didn’t just ask for your phone or something, because your brain was focused on those three words. He’d said he wasn’t going to wait for her call. Not this time. Not this time. Not this time. Even after he said goodbye and walked away, the words rang in your head.

You weren’t oblivious to the fact that he was going to be hurt by your leaving. But it was different to hear it coming from him.
